ruhe, Baden-Wuerttemberg, Germany":"Bretten, Karlsruhe, Baden-Württemberg, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hechel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["South German: topographic name for someone who lived by a stream, from a diminutive of   Bach   1. This surname is rare in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Bach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Hans, Kurt, Fritz, Klaus, Horst, Johann, Alfons, Bernhard, Erna, Ernst.","German: topographic name for someone who lived by a stream, Middle High German <i>bach</i> ‘stream’. This surname is also found in some other European countries, most notably in Denmark and France (Alsace and Lorraine), but also in e.g. the Netherlands, Czechia (see also 5 below), and Croatia.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial name from German <i>Bach</i> ‘stream, creek’."]},{"name":"Beckel","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Bechel  .","German: variant of <b>Böckel</b> (see   Boeckel  ) and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]}]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anna Hechel was born in 1500, in Ottenhausen, Straubenhardt, Enzkreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany. She married Martin Miller in 1514. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in November 1542, in Bretten, Karlsruhe, Baden-Württemberg, Germany, at the age